In his speech at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York, President Biden thanked the Governor of New York, Kathy Hochul, and the Director of the Met, Max Hollein, for their contributions to the success of the United Nations General Assembly. He emphasized the challenges faced by the world, including the climate crisis and the COVID-19 pandemic, and the importance of upholding principles such as sovereignty and human rights. The President also condemned the recent attack on Ukraine by a member of the United Nations Security Council. He urged leaders to come together and address these challenges, highlighting the need for cooperation between the public and private sectors. He expressed gratitude for the efforts made by leaders to support vulnerable populations and called for continued action to address issues such as conflict, climate change, and corruption. President Biden stressed the need for partnership and investment to achieve goals such as ending hunger, reducing poverty, and promoting gender equality. He concluded by referencing a poem by Seamus Heaney and expressing hope that, by working together, we can shape a better future for humanity.